commit 4d615e8c1ef5eda57d69f0a4576020860b87e200
Author: Jarred Sumner <jarred@jarredsumner.com>
Date:   2026-04-28T11:17:26Z

    fetch: experimental HTTP/3 client via `protocol: "http3"` (#29795)
    
    > [!WARNING]
    > **Highly experimental.** Only exercised by the test suite in this PR.
    
    Adds `fetch(url, { protocol: "http3" | "h3" })`, an lsquic-backed HTTP/3
    client that runs on the HTTP thread alongside the existing H1/H2 paths.
    
    ```ts
    const res = await fetch("https://example.com/", { protocol: "http3" });
    ```
    
    ## Architecture
    
    ```
    fetch()  ──► HTTPClient.start_()
                    │ force_http3?
                    ▼
             H3.ClientContext  (one lsquic client engine per HTTP-thread loop)
                    │
                    ├─ ClientSession  (one QUIC conn per (origin, rejectUnauthorized), pooled)
                    │     └─ Stream   (1:1 with HTTPClient; bound when lsquic hands out a stream id)
                    │
                    └─ PendingConnect (DNS-cache miss → async resolve → lsquic_engine_connect)
    ```
    
    The result-delivery surface is the existing `handleResponseMetadata` /
    `handleResponseBody` / `progressUpdate` pipeline, so redirects,
    decompression and `FetchTasklet` are shared with H1/H2. `Protocol` is
    now `enum(u2){http1_1,http2,http3}`; the multiplexed-transport guards in
    `doRedirect` / `sendProgressUpdateWithoutStageCheck` check `!=
    .http1_1`.
    
    ### usockets / lsquic (`packages/bun-usockets/src/quic.{c,h}`)
    
    The server-only QUIC adapter gains client mode:
    
    - `us_create_quic_client_context()` — `LSENG_HTTP` engine, TLS-1.3
    SSL_CTX with `SSL_CTX_set_custom_verify`. lsquic skips its own
    `ea_verify_cert` when we supply an SSL_CTX, so the verify callback walks
    `lsquic_ssl_to_conn` → `lsquic_conn_get_ctx` to read the
    **per-connection** `reject_unauthorized` + SNI hostname and runs
    `X509_verify_cert` + `X509_check_host` against the system store.
    - `us_quic_socket_context_connect()` — IP literal / `Bun__addrinfo_get`
    cache hit connects synchronously; cache miss returns a
    `us_quic_pending_connect_s` that the Zig side registers with the DNS
    cache via a new `.quic` `DNSRequestOwner` variant (`dns.zig`). No
    blocking `getaddrinfo`.
    - `us_quic_socket_make_stream()`, `on_hsk_done`, per-conn ext, client
    UDP endpoints freed inline on conn close.
    - `us_quic_stream_write` now `lsquic_stream_flush`es:
    `lsquic_stream_write` only buffers, and without a flush the connection
    isn't marked tickable — small streamed writes (in either direction) sat
    until the 1 s CID-throttle alarm. Affects both this client **and**
    `Bun.serve({h3:true})` streamed responses.
    - `us_loop_run_bun_tick` (epoll/kqueue) folds `quic_next_tick_us` into
    the poll timeout so QUIC retransmit/idle timers fire on the HTTP thread,
    which previously had no QUIC timer integration.
    
    ### `src/http/H3Client.zig` (new)
    
    `ClientContext` / `ClientSession` / `Stream` / `PendingConnect`
    mirroring `H2Client.zig`. Streaming request bodies drain the same
    `ThreadSafeStreamBuffer` H2 uses; `HTTPThread.drainQueuedWrites` routes
    write notifications with no abort-tracker socket to
    `H3.ClientContext.streamBodyByHttpId`, and `drainEvents` drains
    DNS-resolved pending connects.
    
    ## Tests
    
    - `test/js/web/fetch/fetch-http3-client.test.ts` — 39 tests against a
    `Bun.serve({ h3: true, h1: false })` subprocess (UDP-only; `beforeAll`
    asserts TCP is refused so a fall-back to H1 fails the whole suite).
    Covers GET/POST/PUT/DELETE/HEAD, headers, JSON, route params, gzip,
    redirects, 1 MB request/response round-trips, 50-way concurrent
    multiplexing, sequential reuse, ReadableStream upload, **full-duplex
    bidirectional streaming** (server starts responding while the upload is
    still open), DNS hostname connect, abort, and `rejectUnauthorized`
    (default-true rejects the self-signed test cert; `false` succeeds).
    - `test/js/bun/http/serve-protocols.test.ts` — adds an `http/3 (native)`
    row so the protocol-agnostic matrix runs over the native client as well
    as curl.
    
